Today, most enterprise environments still rely heavily on Active Directory for authentication.
Every time a user logs in, accesses a file share, or authenticates to a server, protocols like Kerberos, NTLM, and LDAP are used behind the scenes through domain controllers.

Now the problem is — attackers also target identity.”

Pause.

“Techniques like Pass-the-Hash, Golden Ticket, credential theft, and lateral movement all abuse Active Directory authentication flows.

This is where Microsoft Defender for Identity comes in.”

🔹 What It Is

“MDI is a cloud-based identity threat detection solution that monitors on-premises Active Directory signals.

It works by installing an MDI sensor directly on Domain Controllers and AD FS servers.

These sensors analyze:

Active Directory entities

Parsed network traffic

Windows security events

Authentication patterns like Kerberos and LDAP

All this telemetry is sent to the Microsoft 365 Defender portal for analysis.”

🔹 What It Protects

“MDI protects:

• Hybrid identities — both on-prem AD and cloud-synced identities
• Directory services like Active Directory, AD FS, and AD CS
• Authentication flows such as Kerberos and NTLM

So instead of just monitoring endpoints, MDI monitors the identity infrastructure itself.”

Strong line:

“Because if identity is compromised, the attacker owns the network.”



-----------------------------------------------------------------------

“Now let’s look at what MDI actually does.”

🔹 Key Capabilities

“First, User and Entity Behavior Analytics (UEBA).

MDI builds behavioral profiles of users and detects anomalies — for example:

A user logging in from unusual locations

Abnormal LDAP queries

Suspicious privilege escalation”

“Second, Lateral Movement Detection.

If an attacker steals credentials and starts moving between servers using Kerberos tickets, MDI detects that pattern immediately.”

“Third, Security Posture Management.

It identifies risky AD configurations such as:

Unconstrained delegation

Weak protocols

Misconfigured service accounts”

“Fourth, Advanced Attack Detection.

It detects sophisticated attacks like:

Pass-the-Hash

Golden Ticket

Reconnaissance attacks inside AD”

🔹 Organizational Value

“From a business perspective, MDI provides:

• Identity-centric security — protecting the most targeted attack vector
• Faster investigation with a clear attack timeline
• Native integration with Microsoft Defender XDR

This means identity alerts are correlated with endpoint, email, and cloud signals.”

🔹 Strong Closing Line

“So in simple terms,

If MDE protects the device,
And Sentinel centralizes visibility,

MDI protects the identity layer — which is often the attacker’s primary objective.”



